Its Valentine’s week, which means my feed (and probably yours) is over run with heart shaped this and chocolate that and pink this. Well — this is me adding 1 more in. If you plan on baking this Valentines day, or at least want to bake something cute to bring into the office like what I’m doing, these blood orange bars are great choice! Blood oranges are in season right now and have that beautiful pinkish-red hue that makes my heart flutter. Its essentially a shortbread cookies + a baked curd, so what can go wrong! If you’ve had lemon bars before, its a very similar taste and feel, but slightly less tart!

---

![Side image of bars](./berry_rhubarb_bars.jpg)
![Berry Rhubarb bars](./berry_rhubarb_bars-4.jpg)
![Berry Rhubarb Bars](./strawberry_rhubarb_bars-3.jpg)
![Berry Rhubarb Bars](./strawberry_rhubarb_bars-2.jpg)



These bars are super easy to make and a great summer dessert! Feel free to use either fresh or frozen fruit.  If you use fresh strawberries and/or berries, the texture will be a bit more chunky than frozen (seen in photos 3 and 4).  From my experiments, frozen fruit will break down easier and form more of a jam like texture (seen in photos 1 and 2). The recipe says to use 450g of strawberries and 350g of rhubarb.  If you don't have that much rhubarb (it's expensive yo!), replace some of the weight with raspberries, blueberries or more strawberries! Any combo will be delicious.

internal.content:
--- ![Social View](./mole_cheesecake-13.jpg) ![Slice View](./mole_cheesecake-34.jpg)
The first month of the New Year has already flown by and it’s bitter cold here in Brooklyn. Even though winter is always fun (ie. skiing), I get that yearning to be on a beach in Mexico or basking in the Mediterranean sun whenever I am trudging to work through the snowy dirty streets of New York. Making and eating this Mexican Ricotta Cheesecake with a Tomato Mole Jam is possibly the next best thing to hopping on a flight to warmer weather. It has loads of spicy, complex flavors that will keep you warm and preoccupied until the sun comes out in a few months. When i was approached by Muir Glen and The Feedfeed to develop a recipe for them using their organic canned tomatoes, I wanted to think outside the box. Wanting to stay true to my *mostly* dessert feed, a tomato jam immediately came to mind. Tomato jams are usually made with onions, cumin and other savory spices. They show up on cheese plates, as condiments for sandwiches, on top of eggs and in vinaigrettes. I wanted to make a more complex, sweeter jam that could do double duty as a perfect addition to a cheese plate but not feel weird on top of a dessert. Mole is a traditional sauce used in Mexican cuisines. According to Wikipedia - the source of all knowledge - a mole sauce contains a fruit, chili pepper, nut, and such spices as black pepper, cinnamon, cumin, and chocolate. I could work with that. As you can see in the final recipe below, my mole jam has a lot of that - cinnamon, dried fruit, almonds and cocoa. The results? A sweet, (but not too sweet!) dynamic, interesting jam with a slightly spicy aftertaste. It tastes like a tomato jam, but it also doesn’t really taste a whole lot like what you would think tomatoes taste like. But what do I put it on?
Enter the ricotta cheesecake. Using ricotta in place of some of the cream cheese makes the cake a lot lighter (in a calorie and fluffier way). This creates a good balance with the graham cracker crust and thick dense mole jam. By using the tried and true water bath method (outlined in the instructions), my cheesecake came out perfect with no cracks, no overcooked edges and a flat top! I also left it in the oven after I turned off the heat for a few hours, which I’ve read helps prevent cracking. I ventured to my local co-op to buy the tomatoes, spices and other ingredients for this recipe. Flatbush Food Coop is the closest one to me, but you can find your closest one here! The tomatoes are currently on sale for 10/$10 - which is very exciting because that’s almost half their regular price. Speaking of deals (which I’m a huge fan of), the entire co-op was extremely reasonably priced and they had an extensive bulk food and spice section where you can get just what you need (like for this recipe!). This cake is perfect when you want to try making something different. The jam itself is a showstopper and I can imagine it works very well with all sorts of cheese, on top of your morning bagel and cream cheese, inside a pastry or mixed into yogurt. The jam makes a little more than you actually need to cover the cake, so let me know if you make this recipe and what you did with the extra!
![Top View with can](./mole_cheesecake-18.jpg) ![Slice with bite View](./mole_cheesecake-36.jpg) This post is sponsored by [Muir Glen](https://www.muirglen.com/) and [The Feedfeed](https://thefeedfeed.com/), but all opinions are my own.

B2NTVm_lbhY.caption:
Carrot Coconut Cake w/ Honey Cream Cheese Frosting: I made this cake a few weeks ago for one of my closest friends and overall awesome person @iamdopico ’s birthday.  She always tells me she doesn’t eat sweets (its a shock we’re still friends) except for my baked goods. I guess I should be flattered 😏 So therefore for her birthday I decided on a carrot cake, cutting the sugar a bit and used a cream cheese frosting that is solely sweetened with honey. The sunflowers were fun to make and I tried to go for those Van Gough vibes.
.
Carrot cake is a combo of @testkitchen and @livforcake ’s recipes for carrot cake (with some added coconut 🥥🤟🏻) Honey cream cheese frosting is from America’s test kitchen as well. The flowers are made with plain ol’ american buttercream in order to keep their shape.
.
.
.

B5ls02Tl-dv.caption:
Pecan Pie Cheesecake w/ Dulce de Leche: I know I’m a few days late to #thanksgivingdessert content and have been a little quiet on here, but I wanted to share this cheesecake that I made for a friendsgiving last week hosted by some lovely friends in NYC.  This is a pecan pie cheesecake swirled with dulce de leche. When I saw @studiobaked post the recipe for this on her feed I instantly knew I had to make it. We had a signup sheet for this friendsgiving and pie was already accounted for, so this was perfect.  I was told it was the best cheesecake they’ve ever had by multiple people, so folks this is a keeper. The cheesecake was oh so creamy and perfectly complemented the pecan topping and graham cracker pecan crust. 🧀🍰
.
.

Bake Sale Raspberry Macarons : My office had a bake sale today to benefit Breast Cancer Awareness Month (all of October) and I made these lil pink macarons as my contribution to the sale.  In total we raised almost $1000 for the @suzangkomen foundation! (these alone made $100+ of that 💁🏼‍♀️) All of the baked goods looked great and the ones I tried were so delicious! It was awesome seeing people lined up to buy treats, with most of them gone within an hour. -- I also made a donation to @bcrfcure today and encourage anyone who sees this to donate directly to any of the foundations that fund breast cancer research or provide services/resources.  Theres still half the month left so get to it! Swipe to see some of the goods other people brought!
.
I added 10g of ground freeze-dried raspberries, replacing some of the powdered sugar in a vanilla macaron shell recipe.  The buttercream is a german buttercream with rose water + raspberry extract. Base shell recipe from @cloudykitchen & @foxandcrane .
.

B0XCZealoAg.caption:
Throwing it back this Thursday to some of the finished goods I made in a 3 day laminating class I took with my mom a few weeks ago at the King Arthur Flour baking school in Vermont. 🥐 Im starting to look into bike routes for when I go back to Vermont next weekend with my Dad and craving these croissants that are loooong gone.  Seriously though, Vermont has all of my favorite things - baking, biking, beer, bomb ass cheese, beautiful hikes.. .
Surprisingly the process of laminating dough (the act of creating layers of dough and butter that create flakey pastries) was a lot easier than expected, just a lot of waiting times between rolling/folding.  These came out perfect, but I was under guidance of amazing teachers who also knew exactly when to pull them out of the oven. I am excited to try it on my own soon, but may have to wait for the temp to cool so it doesn’t turn into a pool of butter 🤷‍♀️ If you missed my instagram stories of the class, they can be found in the highlights!
.

B13vOZGFkSQ.caption:
Raspberry Apricot Scones: Happy LDW! I’m taking it easy this holiday weekend, catching up on sleep, friends and books I got to finish for bookclub 😬 These scones are a perfect way to start a lazy Sunday morning.  The recipe is @kingarthurflour ’s master scone recipe with 1 cup of Raspberry jammy bits (also from KAF!) and 1 cup of chopped dried apricots mixed in.  I am a big fan of their jammy bits (and I love saying it outloud), since they are basically fruit puree + sugar and melt a bit during baking, giving the scones a little bit of jam in every bite! .
I also made some fig jam to accompany these scones, and they were **chefs kiss** together
.
.

B1r5Lddlvn3.caption:
Fig and Cherry Plum Galette: I cant believe it’s only just Tuesday 😒 I spent most of the day trying to remember how Java works (the programming language) since I’ve been mostly writing in JavaScript (and Python) the past few years at my job. It was a real struggle trying to remember how types work and it gave me not so great flashbacks to my college Computer Science classes. At least I have some of this galette left at home to try and block any further trips down memory of all the all-nighters I had to pull. This galette is not too sweet, super easy to make and is perfect for any time of day 🤙🏼
.
To make it, slice figs and @traderjoes cherry plums and toss with ½ tsp vanilla, 1 tsp lemon juice, 3 tbsp sugar, 1 tsp cornstarch and let sit for 10 min. I pulled out some pie dough from the freezer, recipe from @birdsblack - rolled out to a circle 1/8th of an inch. Arrange fruit on dough and fold in the dough on all sides. Refrigerate for 30 min.  Brush sides with egg wash and sprinkle sparkling sugar. bake at 375 for 35-40 or until golden. .
.

B1KaiyKFPMF.caption:
Buckeye Balls ✨: I recently joined a group of friends who were doing a monthly bookclub and it was finally my turn to host last week! I chose the book ‘Little Fires Everywhere’ by @pronounced_ing which I tremendously enjoyed.  It was overall an easy and enjoyable read with a bunch of interesting themes for us to talk about 💁🏼‍♀️ I think its gonna make a great TV adaptation, coming to @hulu soon. Well the story takes place in Shaker Heights Ohio, and these sugary indulgent balls are a true Ohio staple. I glitzed them up with some sprinkles and @wiltoncakes gold spray ! I served alongside a ton of cheese, crackers and beet goat cheese hummus 🤙🏼
.
 If you’ve read Little Fires Everywhere what did you think of it?!
.
Buckeye Balls - makes ~ 30
1 container (1.5 cups) of peanut butter
4 cups of powdered sugar
1 1/2 tsp vanilla extract
1 tsp cinnamon
1/2 cup of butter
8 oz dark chocolate
1 Tbsp shortening or coconut oil
Sprinkles
.
Combine first 5 ingredients in a bowl. Using a 2 tsp cookie scoop, create balls and place on a sheet pan lined with wax/parchment paper. Refrigerate for 30 min. Using a double broiler or microwave, melt chocolate and shortening until smooth.  Using a toothpick, dip each ball into the chocolate and return to pan. Add sprinkles. Refrigerate another 30 min and enjoy!
.

BzeKFZrFKDO.caption:
Apple Galette w/ Vermont Maple Syrup 🍎 🥐: My mom and I are currently on our third and last day of a “Laminating Pastry Intensive Workshop” at @kingarthurflour ‘s baking school in Norwich, VT. I’ve done a few classes here before, but I’m constantly impressed every time. Their cafe, school and shop (which is a great exercise in practicing self control) are all awesome. I’ve been posting snippets from the class on my stories and they will be in the highlights 🤙🏼
.
The first day we learned how to make a blitz (rough) puff and prepped all the dough for various pastries. A blitz puff uses flattened cubes of butter folded in instead of a sheet of butter, then a few folds all at once to mimic a puff pastry. This Apple galette uses said blitz pastry and was brushed with maple syrup 🍁 right out of the oven 🤤 Second photo were turnovers using the blitz that we stuffed with tomato sauce, caramelized onions and spinach.

B6ReG5Ilr2_.caption:
Pecan Brittle Bark Cookies:  Holiday baking is in full effect in my apartment, and these babies are making an appearance.  The recipe is a little involved - you make hard pecan caramel that gets broken up and made into a dark chocolate caramel bark.  The bark is then used instead of chocolate chips in the cookie recipe.  It so good, the flavors are so much more elevated than a typical CCC, and the brown sugar/oil ratios give it a really soft but perfect texture when you bite into it. Recipe is from #thecookiebook by @displacedhousewife ! .
Im planning on staying in NYC for the holidays, but going to spend Christmas with my good friend in the suburbs, so the next few days will be filled with preparing the most epic of cookie containers for her family.  Im super looking forward to it.  Cookies are the best gifts you can give 🍪💌
.
.

BzJlKQjFfvA.caption:
Dulce de Leche Stuffed Chocolate Chunk Cookies (Baked + recipe): These babies have a mix of milk and dark chocolate @guittardchocolate discs, flaky salt on top and a healthy dollop of dulce de leche inside 🤟🏻 what more can you ask for out of this Tuesday? .
The recipe is up on full stack kitchen! https://www.fullstackkitchen.com/dulce-de-leche-chocolate-chunk-cookies/ . 
The name of the blog is a play on the fact that I’m a full stack developer / engineer and am going to be working on adding cool features to the blog as i grow it. 
I’ve been starting to post my recipes on it, but it still very much is a work in progress!  I finally got the url issues fixed and happy with the way I deploy the site to production! (just 1 terminal command that updates a static site branch on GitHub that updates the site) and then there was also a whole thing with someone asking me out on GitHub using the codebase that hosts this blog 🙄 guess comes with the territory. Cookies make things better is the moral of the story. .
.
.

Bzyz5yPFzkw.caption:
Rhubarb Almond Frangipane Tart w/ Cherry Rhubarb Jam: I know rhubarb season is almost over, but I just needed to buy some when I saw a full table of it at the farmers market a little while back. This tart has a flakey shortbread crust, a sweet rich almond frangipane (frangipane is  basically made up of flour + almonds + eggs + sugar + butter), strips of bright red and green rhubarb, and brushed with homemade cherry rhubarb jam! Rhubarb is one of those ingredients that always gets me so excited whenever I see it at the markets, and I’m always sad when the season is over.  So make the most of summer! .
Recipe for this tart is from @theflouredtable (search rhubarb frangipane tart) - I had to use up some cherries so I made the jam (basically 2/3 cherries, 1/3 rhubarb + sugar + lemon cooked down) that I brushed on top. Turned out great and I have more jam for a different project!

**hi, Welcome to my little corner of the internet.  my name is tara.**

I have been a resident of New York City for the past five years, currently living in Williamsburg, Brooklyn.  Before that, I spent the first eighteen years of my life in South Florida dealing with humidity.  Then I spent four in Philadelphia for college, where I discovered and honed my love of baking while procrastinating problem sets.  Many times I would be making muffins at midnight to break up the _all too frequent_ all-nighters I pulled.

I studied Computer Science/Computer Graphics in school (+ a fine arts minor) and am currently a full time, full stack Software Engineer for a media company. Having an office to bring sweets to is key to maintaining a healthy lifestyle. To counteract what doesn't make it into the office, I am constantly trying to find ways to be exercising.  I am an avid runner, biker (I stubbornly CitiBike to work most days), and walk everywhere.  Right now I've completed 6 half marathons and 1 century ride!

If we can get nerdy for a second, I am very proud of this website you see here. The "tech stack", as one would say, is pretty cool.  I am using [React](https://reactjs.org/), which is a component based Javascript library for building UI's. That is wrapped in an instance of [GatsbyJs](https://www.gatsbyjs.org/), which is a React-based, [GraphQL](https://graphql.org/) powered, static site generator (makes for better SEO and file hosting!).  All the posts are written in [markdown](https://github.com/adam-p/markdown-here/wiki/Markdown-Cheatsheet), which is a lightweight markup language for text syntax.  Once I make updates and build it, it hooks into [GitHub Pages](https://pages.github.com/) and automatically updates the site!
